'''''Manu militari''''' is a [[Latin]] term, meaning "by military means".
It is used in the legal language, where it indicates the use of the public strength in order to enforce a sentence.
It is also used by many authors (e.g. [[Julius Caesar]] in the ''[[De bello gallico]]''), as well as in common speech, often in the [[locution]] "ipso facto et manu militari", meaning "right now and by any means necessary".